Cell-phone driving laws are having limited success in passage.
Federal bills died in committee.
Without a national consensus, existing state and local government laws vary widely.
Drivers either ignore or are unaware of existing laws.
Enforcement is not uniform.
Lobbyists oppose legislation and argue driver distraction by various factors is at fault not cell-phone technology.
A survey of cell phone records and accidents in Australia conducted by the U.S. based Insurance Institute for Highway Safety concludes that there is little difference between hand-held and hands-free device driver distraction.
The survey confirms that cell-phone use while driving increases injuries and deaths.
